    "# Stock Performance Analyzer V2\n",
    "\n",
    "**Author** Bryan White\n",
    "\n",
    "**Goal** Pull real historical stock data, calculate key performance results, and visualize results with Python\n",
    "\n",
    "This project uses the following libraries:\n",
    "- `yfinance` - fetches real stock data from Yahoo Finance (S&P supplies the Market Data here, so I know this data very well)\n",
    "- `pandas` - data manipulation and analysis\n",
    "- `matplotlib` / `seaborn` - data visualization"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "36531add-5f17-40c4-a66e-0e64fb852aae",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Step 1: Import Libraries\n",
    "\n",
    "- `yfinance` gives us access to live market data\n",
    "- `pandas` is our main data manipulation tool (think of it as Python's version of Excel/SQL)\n",
    "- `matplotlib` and `seaborn` handle our charts\n",
    "- `datetime` lets us work with dates cleanly"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "fdacd6c0-f1a0-4542-90f7-2a75f9eed800",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "All libraries loaded successfully!\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import yfinance as yf\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "from datetime import datetime, timedelta\n",
    "\n",
    "# this makes our chart render cleanly inside the notebook\n",
    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "\n",
    "# setting clean visual style for ALL charts\n",
    "sns.set_theme(style='whitegrid')\n",
    "plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (12, 6)\n",
    "\n",
    "print('All libraries loaded successfully!')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a1b9692f-3fd5-4a27-b582-516abe819589",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Step 2: Define our Equities and Date Range\n",
    "\n",
    "I'm going to look at 5 well known equities of companies that are in the S&P 500 index. The S&P 500 ETF (SPY) is also going to be my **benchmark** index that I will return data for along side the other 4 equities.\n",
    "\n",
    "My date range is going to be year, so today's date - 365 days. This will be a rolling history forward, since the date functions I will use will use the current date when a user will run the Python code in this Jupyter Notebook.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "a6c17349-112c-458a-8963-8e6c22614893",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Pulling data from 2025-05-13 to 2026-05-13\n",
      "Tickers: ['MSFT', 'AAPL', 'JPM', 'GS', 'SPY']\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Define our equity population using ticker symbol as the identifier\n",
    "tickers = ['MSFT', 'AAPL', 'JPM', 'GS', 'SPY']\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Setting my date range: today going back one year\n",
    "end_date = datetime.today()\n",
    "start_date = end_date - timedelta(days=365)\n",
    "# print(start_date, end_date)\n",
    "# you can test if your date function is returning the correct start_date & end_date HERE\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Format dates as strings (yfinance expects this date format 'YYYY-MM-DD')\n",
    "start_str = start_date.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')\n",
    "end_str = end_date.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')\n",
    "# print(start_str, end_str)\n",
    "# you can test if your date function is returning the correct start_date & end_date HERE, notice how there is no longer a timestamp\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f'Pulling data from {start_str} to {end_str}')\n",
    "print(f'Tickers: {tickers}')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3f11a56e-392f-4b1b-b121-b203d4651b59",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
