   "source": [
    "# Step 4: Daily Returns\n",
    "\n",
    "Raw price tells us what a stock costs at market value. However, **Daily return** tells us how much a stock moved each day as a percentage (%). This is how we measure stock performance apples-to-apples across different-priced stocks.\n",
    "\n",
    "I used `pct_change()`, which is a Pandas method that calculates the percentage change from one row to the next. One line of code does what would take many lines of SQL, so it is very handy."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "id": "dba002e9-5ed5-4b67-9e06-6abf62b52c2b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Sample values (should be small decimals, not hundreds):\n",
      "Ticker          AAPL        GS       JPM      MSFT       SPY\n",
      "Date                                                        \n",
      "2025-05-14 -0.002818  0.012901  0.010000  0.008461  0.001278\n",
      "2025-05-15 -0.004144  0.007031  0.006964  0.002256  0.004884\n",
      "2025-05-16 -0.000899  0.005082  0.000262  0.002516  0.006334\n",
      "2025-05-19 -0.011739 -0.010872 -0.010016  0.010126  0.001094\n",
      "2025-05-20 -0.009196 -0.009440  0.003020 -0.001525 -0.003362\n",
      "\n",
      "Mean values (should be near 0.0):\n",
      "Ticker\n",
      "AAPL    0.001418\n",
      "GS      0.002020\n",
      "JPM     0.000757\n",
      "MSFT   -0.000244\n",
      "SPY     0.000992\n",
      "dtype: float64\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Calculate daily percentage returns\n",
    "# .squeeze() handles newer yfinance column structures\n",
    "daily_returns = prices.pct_change().squeeze()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Drop the first row (NaN since there's no previous day to compare)\n",
    "daily_returns = daily_returns.dropna()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Verify it worked - values should be small decimals like 0.01, -0.02\n",
    "print(\"Sample values (should be small decimals, not hundreds):\")\n",
    "print(daily_returns.head())\n",
    "print(\"\\nMean values (should be near 0.0):\")\n",
    "print(daily_returns.mean())"
   ]
  },
