    "## Step 9: Findings & Takeaways\n"
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Findings & Takeaways\n",
    "\n",
    "**1. Top Performer: Goldman Sachs (GS)**\n",
    "GS was the clear standout with a 59.90% total return over the past year,\n",
    "more than doubling the SPY benchmark return of 27.23%. This likely reflects\n",
    "the strong environment for investment banking, M&A activity, and trading\n",
    "revenue that benefited the major Wall Street banks over this period.\n",
    "\n",
    "**2. Benchmark Beaters vs. Laggards**\n",
    "\n",
    "Three of five stocks beat the SPY benchmark:\n",
    "- GS: +59.90% (beat SPY by +32.67%)\n",
    "- AAPL: +39.00% (beat SPY by +11.77%)\n",
    "- JPM: +18.17% (underperformed SPY by -9.06%)\n",
    "- MSFT: -8.52% (underperformed SPY by -35.75%)\n",
    "\n",
    "**3. Best Risk-Adjusted Return: \n",
    "SPY**\n",
    "\n",
    "Despite not having the highest raw return, SPY had the best Sharpe-like\n",
    "ratio at 0.1308 — meaning it delivered the most return per unit of risk.\n",
    "GS had high returns but also the highest volatility (1.68%), so on a\n",
    "risk-adjusted basis, the index actually wins. This is a classic lesson in\n",
    "investing: raw returns don't tell the whole story.\n",
    "\n",
    "**4. Most Surprising Result: MSFT**\n",
    "\n",
    "Microsoft's -8.52% return was the most surprising finding. As one of the\n",
    "largest companies in the S&P 500 and a leader in AI infrastructure, a\n",
    "negative return over this period likely reflects valuation compression after\n",
    "years of outsized growth — a reminder that strong businesses don't always\n",
    "mean strong near-term stock performance.\n",
    "\n",
    "**5. If Forced to Pick One**\n",
    "\n",
    "Based purely on this data, GS offers the most compelling case — strong\n",
    "absolute return with a reasonable Sharpe ratio. However, SPY's superior\n",
    "risk-adjusted performance makes it the more defensible long-term choice,\n",
    "which is why it remains the standard benchmark against which everything else is measured.\n",
